										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">We can create the structure of a website and its headings, paragraphs, and links in HTML. When creating a varied and well-structured website, you have to consider other aspects besides transparency—colors, for example.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">We have already written an </span><a href="https://codeberryschool.com/blog/en/introduction-to-web-development/" data-wpel-link="external" target="_blank" rel="external"><span style="font-weight: 400;">introduction to web development</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;">, so you should look through that article if you are interested in the basics of HTML.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">In this post, we’re going to look at how you can define colors and shades in the HTML color codes, with a lot of sample illustrations.</span></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><a href="https://codeberryschool.com/en/all-access-self-paced" target="_blank" rel="noopener external" data-wpel-link="external"><img loading="lazy" class="aligncenter wp-image-12254 size-full" src="https://codeberryschool.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Self-paced-1.png" alt="" width="1024" height="340" srcset="/blog/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Self-paced-1.png 1024w, /blog/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Self-paced-1-300x100.png 300w, /blog/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Self-paced-1-768x255.png 768w" sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" /></a></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400;">HTML color codes&#8217; names</span></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">There are millions of shades of color that can be displayed by modern browsers. It would be impossible to name and account for all of them, so in the world of IT, we use codes to define colors and shades.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">HTML supports 140 </span><a href="https://www.tutorialspoint.com/html/html_color_names.htm" target="_blank" rel="noopener external" data-wpel-link="external"><span style="font-weight: 400;">standard color names</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;">, but you can define any other shade on your website as well, using color codes. Pre-coded colors can be defined by their specific color names (like aqua, black, yellowgreen, hotpink, etc.), so we don’t need to search for any specific codes to define exactly those colors.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">There are multiple coding systems for colors, and these codes contain the ratio of different components (base colors) and the value of parameters (e.g., transparency or saturation). In this article, we’ll show you the hexadecimal system in detail and we will only mention the other options.</span></p>
<p><div style="width: 955px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><img loading="lazy" class="size-large" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/images.wealthyaffiliate.com/uploads/953826/wysiwyg/training/81e7dab23b371169feb09cdd7492853a_1502874892_cropped.jpg" alt="With HTML color codes we can create endless diversity of colorful illustrations." width="945" height="825" /><p class="wp-caption-text">With HTML color codes we can create endless diversity of colorful illustrations.</p></div></p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400;">Color pickers and mixing colors</span></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">We can find color codes using color picker tools.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Here are a few examples of color pickers:</span></p>
<ul>
<li style="font-weight: 400;"><a href="https://www.w3schools.com/colors/colors_picker.asp" target="_blank" rel="noopener external" data-wpel-link="external"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Color palette</span></a></li>
<li style="font-weight: 400;"><a href="https://htmlcolorcodes.com/color-picker/" target="_blank" rel="noopener external" data-wpel-link="external"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Transitions and subtle differences between shades</span></a></li>
<li style="font-weight: 400;"><a href="https://imagecolorpicker.com/en/" target="_blank" rel="noopener external" data-wpel-link="external"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Identifying colors from images</span></a></li>
</ul>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Every color that our eyes can detect is a mixture of different ratios of base colors. In IT, different shades are displayed by mixing the base colors red, green, and blue (RGB).</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">(In color theory, the base colors are red, yellow and blue, but because of some features of computer screens, we have to use other colors in IT.)</span></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400;">Hexadecimal color code </span></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Among all options for color codes, hexadecimal is the most concise, and therefore, the most widely used form when editing HTML code.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">The color code starts with a # character, followed by a series of six characters. We can define the exact color we want to use with numbers (0-9) and letters (a-f). The first two characters define the value of red (RR), the second set of two defines green (GG), and the third set of two defines blue (BB).</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">For example: #eb4034</span></p>
<p><img loading="lazy" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-10299" src="https://codeberryschool.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/hex-code-1.png" alt="" width="852" height="490" srcset="/blog/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/hex-code-1.png 852w, /blog/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/hex-code-1-300x173.png 300w, /blog/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/hex-code-1-768x442.png 768w" sizes="(max-width: 852px) 100vw, 852px" /></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Different shades of grey contain the same amount of all components.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">E.g.,</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">#404040</span></p>
<p><img loading="lazy" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-10300" src="https://codeberryschool.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/hex-code-grey-1-1.png" alt="" width="864" height="480" srcset="/blog/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/hex-code-grey-1-1.png 864w, /blog/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/hex-code-grey-1-1-300x167.png 300w, /blog/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/hex-code-grey-1-1-768x427.png 768w" sizes="(max-width: 864px) 100vw, 864px" /></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">#bebebe</span></p>
<p><img loading="lazy" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-10301" src="https://codeberryschool.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/grey2-1.png" alt="" width="860" height="485" srcset="/blog/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/grey2-1.png 860w, /blog/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/grey2-1-300x169.png 300w, /blog/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/grey2-1-768x433.png 768w" sizes="(max-width: 860px) 100vw, 860px" /></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Each character of the color black is 0 </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">#000000</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">The color white contains the maximal value of all components</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">#ffffff</span></p>
<h3><span style="font-weight: 400;">Shorter hexadecimal values</span></h3>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">There are times when we can use even shorter codes; for colors that have the same characters for each component, we can use only three characters and get the same color. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">The code #000 defines black, just like #000000, while #0ff creates the same turquoise color as #00ffff. </span></p>
<p><img loading="lazy" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-10302" src="https://codeberryschool.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/c24-1.png" alt="" width="854" height="485" srcset="/blog/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/c24-1.png 854w, /blog/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/c24-1-300x170.png 300w, /blog/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/c24-1-768x436.png 768w" sizes="(max-width: 854px) 100vw, 854px" /></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">The shorter version of #cc2244 is #c24</span></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><a href="https://codeberryschool.com/en/all-access-self-paced" target="_blank" rel="noopener external" data-wpel-link="external"><img loading="lazy" class="aligncenter wp-image-12028 size-full" src="https://codeberryschool.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Testimonial-2.png" alt="" width="1024" height="340" srcset="/blog/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Testimonial-2.png 1024w, /blog/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Testimonial-2-300x100.png 300w, /blog/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Testimonial-2-768x255.png 768w" sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" /></a></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400;">Where does the HTML color code go?</span></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">We can define colors in the form of attributes within the tag the color applies to. We can define the background color of the website within the &lt;body&gt; tag, and the color of the main heading should be within the &lt;h1&gt; tag, etc.</span></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<h3><span style="font-weight: 400;">Attributes:</span></h3>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Within the </span><b>&lt;body&gt;</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> tag, we can define the color of the text with the ‘</span><b>text’ </b><span style="font-weight: 400;">attribute, and the color of the background with the </span><b>‘bgcolor’</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> attribute. We can use the </span><b>‘color’</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> attribute within the </span><b>&lt;font&gt;</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> tag to change the color.</span></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><iframe style="width: 100%;" title="html color code en-us1" src="https://codepen.io/le-peters/embed/abmERaj?height=265&amp;theme-id=dark&amp;default-tab=html,result" height="350" frameborder="no" scrolling="no" allowfullscreen="allowfullscreen"><br />
  See the Pen <a href="https://codepen.io/le-peters/pen/abmERaj" target="_blank" rel="noopener external" data-wpel-link="external">html color code en-us1</a> by Le Peters<br />
  (<a href="https://codepen.io/le-peters" target="_blank" rel="noopener external" data-wpel-link="external">@le-peters</a>) on <a href="https://codepen.io/" target="_blank" rel="noopener external" data-wpel-link="external">CodePen</a>.<br /></iframe></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">In HTML, we can use the </span><b>&lt;style&gt;</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> tag in all other elements to overwrite any globally defined information (e.g., format, style, color) to display something different in a specific location.</span></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><iframe style="width: 100%;" title="html color code en-us2" src="https://codepen.io/le-peters/embed/eYdyPQy?height=265&amp;theme-id=dark&amp;default-tab=html,result" height="350" frameborder="no" scrolling="no" allowfullscreen="allowfullscreen"><br />
  See the Pen <a href="https://codepen.io/le-peters/pen/eYdyPQy" target="_blank" rel="noopener external" data-wpel-link="external">html color code en-us2</a> by Le Peters<br />
  (<a href="https://codepen.io/le-peters" target="_blank" rel="noopener external" data-wpel-link="external">@le-peters</a>) on <a href="https://codepen.io/" target="_blank" rel="noopener external" data-wpel-link="external">CodePen</a>.<br /></iframe></p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400;">Other color-coding options</span></h2>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<h3><span style="font-weight: 400;">RGB, RGBA</span></h3>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">We can define the ratio of red, green and blue in a scale from 0 to 255, not just in a hexadecimal form. To do this, we have to put the code behind the </span><b>text, bgcolor</b><span style="font-weight: 400;">, etc. attributes in this form:</span><b> rgb(192,192,192)</b><span style="font-weight: 400;">. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">When using RGBA codes, in addition to the value of base colors, you also have an other component that refers to transparency called the Alpha Channel. The alpha parameter is a number between 0.0 (fully transparent) and 1.0 (not transparent at all). This is how a color looks in RGBA code:  rgba(255, 99, 71, 0.5)</span></p>
<p><img loading="lazy" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-10306" src="https://codeberryschool.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/rgba-1.png" alt="" width="787" height="298" srcset="/blog/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/rgba-1.png 787w, /blog/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/rgba-1-300x114.png 300w, /blog/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/rgba-1-768x291.png 768w" sizes="(max-width: 787px) 100vw, 787px" /></p>
<h3><span style="font-weight: 400;">HSL, HSLA</span></h3>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">In HTML, we can define colors using hue, saturation, and lightness (HSL). The value of a hue is expressed in degrees based on its position on the color wheel.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Saturation is a percentage value, 0% defines a shade of grey, and 100% defines the full color. Lightness is also a percentage value, with 0% being black and 100% being white. HSL color codes look like this:</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">hsl(36, 100%, 50%)</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">An alpha value can also be added, which refers to the transparency of the color.</span></p>
<p><img loading="lazy" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-10307" src="https://codeberryschool.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/hsla-1.png" alt="" width="740" height="286" srcset="/blog/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/hsla-1.png 740w, /blog/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/hsla-1-300x116.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 740px) 100vw, 740px" /></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">You should try different color pickers and color-coding forms to find the one that is best for a project and that you can work with most efficiently. With a bit of practice, you can easily define the prettiest colors on your website.</span></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><a href="https://codeberryschool.com/en/all-access-self-paced" target="_blank" rel="noopener external" data-wpel-link="external"><img loading="lazy" class="aligncenter wp-image-12255 size-full" src="https://codeberryschool.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Self-paced-2.png" alt="" width="1024" height="340" srcset="/blog/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Self-paced-2.png 1024w, /blog/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Self-paced-2-300x100.png 300w, /blog/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Self-paced-2-768x255.png 768w" sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" /></a></p>
